	with a conventional text-editor)



 :b: STRENGTH_PASSIVE :b:
The idea being passive exercises 
(As are done at same time as doing something else: no time commitment)
-- GRIP/ARM STRENGTH --- walking to bathroom/back to brush teeth
	-- use grippers with a gauge OR a rag bundled up in a pinch
	-- 4x2-3 sets, pray/mantra to keep count
	-- go light/heavy days. (can push for 10 second isos at times)
	DOUBLE OVERHAND/DOUBLE UNDERHAND/TWIST/HAND OPENERS 
		( steel-bending grips )
		(press against chest/hip for resistance, these 
		  isometric presses while gripping exercises most of arm)
		-- focus on one side of grip ( 2 finger grips, one sided):
			-- overhand- pointer, underhand-pinkie, twist-thumb
		-- hand openers are stretching fingers, do 1 big set
-- LEG STRENGTH --- flossing
	-- stand in wing-chun stance
	-- pull shoulders towards head, practice front/back bends
		(upper-back only focus shoulders/neck, lower back static)
		(stomach vacuums to some degree on these too)
-- MOBILITY/FLEXIBILITY --- brushing teeth/water pick
	-- back bend, static holds. Lean forward at hip, as not to put 
		weight on lower back. (pivot ribcage)
-- PRESSURE POINTS/KNUCKLES --- standing up/down in some cases
	-- press with knuckles (pinkie side and center) when standing up
	-- pressure points: press with pinkie side knuckle. 
		(grind and twist knuckles)
	-- in reality, a sharpie works for pressure points. 
-- JUGGLING --- hand washing
	-- juggle towel to dry hands, be creative
	-- can 'shot-put' towel, keep one side of towel gripped so 
		it can be pulled back, for target practice
		(works in general to practice short-range target practice)
-- TONGUE EXERCISES --- drinking water
	-- swish water around mouth with tongue to wash mouth out after 
		eating. (can rotate neck too)
-- SELF DEFENSE --- 'the fence/I have to.../I wonder.../be friendly'
	-- (these are mostly to AVOID conflict, or during non-physical 
		confrontations)
	-- 'the fence'- hold hands in a non aggressive gesture in front of
		body to deter/get hands ready in case anything happens
		-- like rubbing palm, a 'fake' gesture 
		-- the presence of a 'barrier' is a deterrent. 
	-- 'I have to...' The common one is "I have to crap",
		the idea being an excuse to leave a given situation
	-- 'I wonder...' (followed by confusing unrelated pondering)
		From Derren Brown, the idea being it breaks peoples 
		concentration on topic at hand.
	-- 'what's that?' same as above, a throw out distraction. 
	-- 'be friendly' - not confrontational. 
-- PASSIVE DRAWING EXERCISE --- 
	while going to the bathroom (yeah) look at something 
	in room (walls, towels, whatever), mentally draw it a few times
	(look away/close eyes when drawing it, see 'DRAWING' section
		below for more exercises) 
	-- literally draw it in mind, line by line. 
	-- will get it wrong, check, see what got wrong, try again. 
	-- shoot for 3x perfect without looking 
		(as time here is limited, whatever in time allotted) 
-- MEMORIZATION:
	beyond the MAJOR SYSTEM for numbers,
	-- remembering shopping lists by making something out of all items, 
	-- closing eyes for a few seconds while walking, remembering 
		what is in front of body those few steps
		(can probably do passive drawing exercises with this one,
			mentally drawing what I saw)
	-- MAJOR system with passwords. 
		(pick a phrase, convert it to number)
	-- for actually memorizing stuff, think of a section of text 
		as small chunks, pick 
		a small section that can be repeated like a chant 
		in mind, repeat it till memorized while doing something 
		else, move on to next chunk ( sometimes need to backtrack,
		takes several minutes per section, but time is spent
		while doing something else more engaging, so 
		it's pretty much zero effort.  ) 
-- PRODUCTION: 
	5 minutes (could be less, trying to get a 'fun' event)
	doing something enjoyable, followed by an indefinite 
	period doing something productive, repeat. 
	(the productive period can be 10 seconds to 10 hours+:
		the idea is priming the mind to keep working,
		and giving a 'rest' period)
-- AVOIDING WRITERS BLOCK:
	2 methods:
	-- fieldstone method: 'collect' ideas when seen throughout 
		life, eventually stitch some of them together to compile 
		them into something. As time is spent collecting,
		forcing writing isn't really done. 
	-- the SMBC (the comic) Zack Wienersmith method:
		the mind stops coming up with new things if it 
		gets no input: keep learning new stuff, the 
		writers block should go away. 
-- EXTRA: 
	-- whistling is meditative (but potentially annoying)
	-- flavored chap stick works as 'cologne' 
	---- Below are needed, as I think it's more beneficial
		to 'count' using something besides numbers to keep time,
		not sure best method yet (was using lotus sutra)
	-- psalm 91 (lotus sutra may work, but learning it's sketchy) 
	-- heart sutra? Lotus sutra is tied to a demon summoning, 
		(literally, the sutra ends with the story of binding 
			a demon)
		this one probably isn't. 
	-- affirmations? daily? 





