 :b: Minimal travel/stuff settup :b:
-----------------------------------------
-- THIS SETTUP IS ULTRA-MINIMAL(NO BAG), WILL NEED TO USE WHAT'S AROUND!!!
--	(this gives a lot of wiggle room if in a situation more is needed)
--------------------
-- EXERCISE/GRIPPERS:
	variable grippers (ones with gauge on them) for exercise/strength,
	see above section on STRENGTH (these are personal preference, 
	in reality basic calisthenics and isometrics don't NEED equiptment)
-- NO-BAG/USE VEST-JACKET (jacket/vest + longseeve thin shirt):
	-- jacket/vest is preferred over backpack 
		 (scottevest, etc) with a compressible bag 
		in pocket (jacket WITH scottevest/vest works)
	-- stuff will be stored on person/in pockets (no bag needed)
	-- a good large jacket: should have room to move around 
		(as will have stuff under it) I use amazon basics puffer, 
		it's cheap but durable (not ideal)
	-- large light longsleeve overshirt 
		(to wear OVER jacket- on it's own if needed)
-- PACKABLE BAG-  
	-- seriously, pack a small (tiny) packable bag in jacket:
		it comes useful so many times.
	-- can store jacket if needed
-- EMERGENCY BLANKET:
	(SOL is best brand, more durable less noisy, non-milar are better)
		-- the trick with emergency blankets is to have a layer 
			between them and body, a jacket is your friend.
		-- This is plastic, so can double as a 
			raincoat/under drying clothes/etc 
		-- tie edges together (with string/rolled up paper) 
			if needed (so doesn't fall off/move around)
			(see below for where to get 'rope')
		-- PACK IN ZIPLOCK BAG. 
		-- FOLD IT IN HALF for if using over legs/etc
			(plastic side up) Can always unfold it
-- SHOES:
	get some that work WITHOUT SOCKS (I use crock variants)
	The reason is, no socks, less to wash. 
		(I can take 1 small pair if needed)
-- HAT:
	packable. I no longer really use a 'knit' hat, but those do work 
	-- wear a bandana UNDER hat- banadana cleans easier. 
	-- WIDE BRIMMED, VENTED (via loose-knit or mesh outlets) 
		(baseball caps work, but don't do much)
-- CLOTHES (1 extra shirt, 1 pair pants):
	THE TRICK: wear all clothes AT SAME TIME when traveling
		(shirts over shirts/pants over pants), only 
		take 1 extra pair, wash clothes when showering, 
		NO UNDERWEAR/EXTRA STUFF (ONLY 1 pair pants/shirt)
	-- the basic fruit-of-loom thin t-shirts (black) work and dry fast
	-- for pants, NO JEANS. Thin walled cotton pants will dry quick,
		but not that fast, quickdry pants are better, 
		I prefer cotton
	-- wash clothes while showering::
		(note, basic hand washing of clothes is rubbing clothes
			against themselves, below method is faster):
		-- can probably wash 1 item per day. (only 2 pieces of 
			clothes:shirt and pants, no socks or underwear)
		-- apply bar-soap/etc to cloths before hand (if at all)
			(bar soap can be applied dry) 
		-- put clothes under water IMMEDIATELY when water is 
			heating up/getting ready (BEFORE getting in shower)
		-- let water drip on them when in shower
		-- occasionally in shower shake/ wring clothes, 
			This does NOT NEED TO BE DONE MUCH
		-- keep water running and washing clothes when drying off
			ONLY stop running water over clothes when leaving 
			bathroom/ready to 'wring out' clothes
			(the idea is the water will passively be rinsing
			clothes when person is doing other things)
		-- if still look dirty(water not coming out clean), 
			wash by hand a bit 
			(rub clothes against itself a bit)
		-- this setup should be near 0 time to wash clothes
		--  DRYING CLOTHES: wring out, then: wrap clothes in towel 
			(hopefully, place has towels) and pat/hit towel 
			a few times (this makes them dry much faster)
		-- let dry on hanger, can put plastic/emergency blanket 
			under them to catch initial possible drips
-- BANDANAS:
	take 2+, they dry super fast, have a million uses 
	( 2 of which are air conditioning (wet, pat on back of shirt,
		wet again, wrap around neck,
	  and warmth- wrap around neck... not most visually appeasing 
		thing, but functional) 
-- CLEANING/MEDICAL:
	-- EARPLUGS!!! (can store in glasses case)
		-- THESE ARE MOST IMPORTANT THING, TAKE A FEW PAIRS
	-- glasses case- can store stuff like sewing needle 
		(store needle embedded in glasses-cleaning-cloth) 
	-- ziplock bags are best containers for pills/supplements 
	-- for toothbrush/etc- makeup bags (the kind that are mesh)
	-- I go all out with tooth-cleaning- oral-b battery powered
		toothbrush with usb-c charging batteries (lasts months)
		a portable water pick/superfloss (floss can be pre-cut)
		toothpaste,
		pre-cut floss and a half toothbrush probably would work.
	-- nail clippers (multi-purpose, store with toothbrush)
	-- mirror- use a 'selfi-mirror', the convex kind
		(small convex mirror, should be smaller than palm)
	-- The head of a shaver works for ultra-minimalism, 
		I use non-battery powered clippers 
	-- if taking soap, stick with a bar (half bar?), can smear it on 
		what needs to be washed DRY, so doesn't get wet. 
	-- if taking a sponge- a cut down brillow-pad/scotch-bright pad 
	-- supplements/pills- store in ziplock bags. 
	-- if want, bring a SPOON (it's versitile, can work as knife)
	-- if want, bring a MILITARY-KEYCHAIN-CAN-OPENER (not needed)
-- DEODORANT/SOAP (chap stick/bar soap/ baking powder)
	-- chapstick is great for cologne, and comes in many smells
		tiny, super hard to break
		(apply like solid cologne)
	-- bar soap (applied dry, so don't gotta deal with it wet)
		is easiest soap to use. 
	-- baking powder: this is bomb, but looks sketchy (white powder)
		-- good applied dry to hair/body too for dry-shower. 
-- VALUABLES/DOCS (moneybelt):
	-- a money belt/something to wear under clothes that can fit 
		phone. This is for all important documents.
-- ZIPLOCK BAGS:
	-- pack extra, can store various loose things
-- COMPASS: 
	-- use a clip-on (carbiner) one, clip too jacket (they are tiny)
	-- DON'T DISREGARD: THIS IS SUPER USEFUL!!!
-- PENS/PAPER PAD:
	-- I like pigma micron pens (take 3, .01-2 size), 
		BIC WORKS FINE
	-- paper pad is NOT needed, I do like one, though. 
		that said: can improvise for stuff to write. 
		(receipts/wrappers/etc for taking notes)
-- ELECTRONICS:
	-- phone,
	-- charger ( can pack backup battery, or not)
	-- mouse- logitec pebble 2 (mouse with 2 year battery life, 
		use usb-rechargable batteries, can connect to phone+pc)
	-- iclever folding keyboard (durable, 70 hour battery life, small)
	-- earpiece (smaller than earphones) 
	-- multi-headed usb-charger (makes life easier)
	-- if want, a windows tablet or small laptop (MUST fit in jacket)
	-- if want a light, nightcore has a TINY one (the 'tube')
		that recharges. 
	-- usb-c to to usb connector for plugging usb-storage in phone.
-- FOOD (dark chocolate/wheat grass/ omega-3 & c/ water bottle):
	-- 100% dark chocolate bars are like energy bars, but 
		go further (acquired taste, take small bites)
	-- wheatgrass juice POWDER goes a long way, and is a 
		portable vegetable. 
	-- omega-3 pills plus vitamin c pills are good. 
	-- probably a plastic bottle is easiest, but personal taste
	-- splashing water on bread/'cold soaking' stuff in plastic
		bags can increase volume of dry good 
		(beyond dampening bread, cold soaking never worked
			great for me, wasn't filling)
	-- in a microwave, splashing water on stuff FIRST makes it
		less dry. 
	-- fasting makes life easier.  
	-- not being picky makes life easier. 
-- IMPROVISED ROPE (twist paper/napkin/fabric)
	-- any material twisted get surprisingly strong, use 
		as a improvised binding tool. 
-- IMPROVISE:
	-- a grocery bag works as a bag in a pinch
	-- bandanas/clothes can be jerry-rigged into a crazy
		number of things: be creative.
	-- string can be made by twisting any paper/fiber/plastic
	-- a small amount of money typically goes further in 
		situations than extra goods, as can be used for a lot. 
	-- look around, be creative. 
	-- towels/cloth/etc can make great padding for sleeping. 
		(IF THEY ARE AROUND, NOT TAKEN WITH)
	




